'''HMS ''Ganges''''' was a 74-gun [[third rate]] [[ship of the line]] of the [[Royal Navy]], launched on 30 March 1782 at [[Rotherhithe]].<ref name="Lavery, SoLv1 p180" /> She was the first ship of the Navy to bear the name. Her first captain was [[Charles Fielding]]. She saw active service from 1782 to 1811, in [[Europe]] and the [[West Indies]].<ref name="SON, Ganges">Ships of the Old Navy, ''Ganges''.</ref>
==French Revolutionary Wars== In 1794, whilst under the command of Captain [[William Truscott]], she and {{HMS|Montagu|1779|2}} captured the French [[corvette]] [[French corvette Jacobine (1794)|''Jacobin'']]. ''Jacobin'' was armed with twenty-four 12-pounder guns, and had a crew of 223 men; she was nine days out of [[Brest, France|Brest]] and taken nothing.<ref>{{London Gazette|date=10 February 1795|issue=13751|startpage=147}}</ref> The Royal Navy took ''Jacobin'' into service as HMS ''Matilda''.
''Ganges'' was part of the squadron commanded by [[John Gell (admiral)|Admiral John Gell]], which escorted a Spanish ship they had captured from the French back to [[Portsmouth]]. The ownership of the ship was a matter of some debate and was not settled until 4 February 1795, when the value of the cargo was put at £935,000. At this time all the crew, captains, officers and admirals received a share of the [[prize money]], [[Samuel Hood, 1st Viscount Hood|Admiral Hood]] taking away £50,000. Besides ''Ganges'', the ships that conveyed the Spanish prize to Portsmouth were {{HMS|St George|1785|2}}, {{HMS|Egmont|1768|2}}, {{HMS|Edgar|1779|2}} and {{HMS|Phaeton|1782|2}}.<ref name="AnReg">Annual Register (1795), Chronicle, p. 6.</ref>
''Ganges'' shared in the prize money from the capture of the French supply ship [[Marsouin (1788 ship)|''Marsouin'']] by {{HMS|Beaulieu|1791|2}} on 11 March 1796.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=13968|startpage=13|date=3 January 1797}}</ref>
''Ganges'' was under the command of Captain [[Thomas Fremantle (admiral)|Thomas Fremantle]] at the [[Battle of Copenhagen (1801)|Battle of Copenhagen]].<ref name="SON, Ganges" /> She had on board a contingent of soldiers from the [[Royal Berkshire Regiment|49th Foot]], commanded by [[Isaac Brock]]. Their mission was to storm the forts at [[Copenhagen]], but the outcome of the naval battle made the assault unnecessary.{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}
==Napoleonic Wars== ''Ganges'' was also present at the [[Battle of Copenhagen (1807)|Second Battle of Copenhagen]] in 1807. She bore the flag of [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] [[Richard Goodwin Keats]], and was commanded by Captain [[Sir Peter Halkett, 6th Baronet|Peter Halkett]]. During the battle Keats placed a portrait of Admiral Nelson on the mizzen mast where it was said to have encouraged officers and men alike despite being covered in the blood and brains of an unfortunate seaman.<ref name="ABO49">{{Cite book | last = Longman |author2=Rees |author3=Orme |author4=Brown |author5=Green |author6=Longman | title = The Annual Biography and Obituary 1835, Volume 29 | publisher = Fisher, Son and Jackson | year = 1837 |page=49}}</ref>
In September 1810, two row-boat luggers, one from {{HMS|Ruby|1776|2}}, under the command of Lieutenant Robert Streatfield, and from ''Ganges'', under the command Lieutenants Stackpole, captured two Danish armed vessels off [[Læsø|Lessoe]]. There were no British casualties.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=16406|startpage=1446|date=18 September 1810}}</ref>
==Fate== She was commissioned as a [[prison ship]] on 12 December 1811 for holding prisoners of war until she was transferred to the [[Transport Board (Royal Navy)|Transport Board]] in 1814. ''Ganges'' was broken up at [[Plymouth]] in 1816.<ref name="Lavery, SoLv1 p180" />
